eland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of London, London, England":"London, Middlesex, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1310–1349":"about 1310–1349","1310–1349":"1310–1349","1351–1384":"1351–1384","1349":"1349","ABT 1340":"about 1340","Abt 1310":"about 1310","1310":"1310","1384":"1384","1351":"1351","All Hallow's, Staining, London, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"London, England, United Kingdom","London, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"London, England, United Kingdom","of London, London, England":"London, Middlesex, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hansard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): of Norman origin, from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Ansard</i> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>; from ancient Germanic <i>ans-</i> ‘(pagan) god’ + <i>ward</i> ‘guard, protector’ or <i>hard-</i> ‘brave, hardy’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hazard","meanings":["English: Anglo-Norman French variant of   Hansard  .","English and French: nickname from Old French, Middle English <i>hasard</i>, <i>hazard</i> ‘game of dice’, perhaps given to a player at hazard, i.e. a gambler, trickster, or rascal. The word probably derives from Arabic <i>az-zahr</i>, from <i>az</i>, assimilated form of the definite article <i>al</i>, + <i>zahr</i> ‘die’. It appears to have been picked up in the Holy Land and brought back to Europe by Provençal crusaders.","English: possibly in some instances of Flemish origin, a nickname from Middle Dutch <i>hasart</i> ‘hare’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Hansard MP,Sheriff London was born about 1310, in London, England, United Kingdom. He married Joan de Cantuar about 1340, in London, Middlesex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1349, in his hometown, at the age of 40."},"et":{"Abt 1310–1349":"umbes 1310–1349","1310–1349":"1310–1349","1351–1384":"1351–1384","1349":"1349","ABT 1340":"umbes 1340","Abt 1310":"umbes 1310","1310":"1310","1384":"1384","1351":"1351","All Hallow's, Staining, London, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","London, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","of London, London, England":"London, Middlesex, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1310–1349":"noin 1310–1349","1310–1349":"1310–1349","1351–1384":"1351–1384","1349":"1349","ABT 1340":"noin 1340","Abt 1310":"noin 1310","1310":"1310","1384":"1384","1351":"1351","All Hallow's, Staining, London, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"London, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","London, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"London, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of London, London, England":"London, Middlesex, England","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1310–1349":"environ 1310–1349","1310–1349":"1310–1349","1351–1384":"1351–1384","1349":"1349","ABT 1340":"environ 1340","Abt 1310":"environ 1310","1310":"1310","1384":"1384","1351":"1351","All Hallow's, Staining, London, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"Londres, Angleterre, 